Distributed Web Infrastructure
Infrastructure Design

When a user types www.foobar.com
, the DNS resolves it to the IP of the load balancer (HAproxy). The request is sent to the load balancer, which distributes the traffic between two servers.

Each server contains a web server (Nginx), an application server, and the application code. The web server receives the request and forwards it to the application server, which processes it.

The application communicates with the MySQL database cluster, where one server acts as the Primary (Master) and the other as a Replica (Slave). The primary handles write operations, while the replica handles read operations.

Why we added these components
Load balancer: to distribute traffic and improve availability
Second server: to handle more traffic and avoid full downtime
Database replica: to improve performance and provide backup
Load Balancer Algorithm

The load balancer can use Round Robin, which distributes requests evenly between servers (one request to each server in order).

Active-Active vs Active-Passive

This setup is Active-Active, meaning both servers handle requests at the same time.

Active-Active: both servers are working and sharing traffic
Active-Passive: one server works, the other waits as backup
Primary-Replica (Master-Slave) Database

The Primary node handles write operations (INSERT, UPDATE).
The Replica node copies data from the primary and is used for read operations.

Issues in this Infrastructure
SPOF: the load balancer is still a single point of failure
Security issues: no firewall and no HTTPS encryption
No monitoring: no system to track performance or failures
